  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Upon Reflection
  author: Kang Hwae-baek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The boundless azure sea
    spills across heaven and earth.
    Its vastness knows no limit,
    yet within it lie the Three Blessed Mountains.
    Fusan leans against the eastern sky—
    visible to the eye, but beyond all grasping.
    Dragons coil in their hidden grottos,
    turtle-serpents make their dwelling.

    Who could seize the great tortoise,
    and still the waves?
    North and south stretch without end,
    while the great roc spreads its wings ninety thousand leagues.

    Ah, the grace of sage-kings!
    In comparison, nothing is more magnanimous.
    To bathe in the river Yi, to dance in the Wind of Wu,
    to soar with feathered splendor before the heavenly court,
    to clear the channels of stagnation and purify the realm of man—
    can such things compare?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Blessed Mountains refer to legendary islands in Chinese mythology said to exist beyond the sea.
  - key: ''
    value: Fusan (Fusang) is a mythical sacred tree in the Far East of Chinese cosmology.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'great roc' (peng) references Zhuangzi's legendary bird that flies ninety thousand leagues.
  - key: ''
    value: Bathing in the river Yi and dancing in the Wind of Wu allude to Confucian sage ideals of harmony with nature and moral cultivation.
